WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:45.060 --> 00:00:46.940
Plasma Youth Sports Games
with Unsuccess of the champion,

00:00:47.300 --> 00:00:49.220
would like to thank Slaven Bilić
for stepping in as the host.

00:00:49.460 --> 00:00:51.660
Bilić is one of the first sponsors,
ambassador and is our biggest promoter.

00:00:51.940 --> 00:00:54.300
He used his life and sports experience
in order to prepare high-quality content

00:00:54.500 --> 00:00:56.660
with his guests for all generations.
Thanks, Nane!

00:00:59.940 --> 00:01:02.300
Our guest today is
Zlatan Ibrahimović.

00:01:02.980 --> 00:01:06.860
One of the greatest, best,
the most attractive,

00:01:07.100 --> 00:01:12.340
the most distinctive, and the most
unique players of modern football.

00:01:12.580 --> 00:01:14.260
And football in general.

00:01:14.460 --> 00:01:19.780
Thank you for agreeing
to be a guest on our show.

00:01:19.980 --> 00:01:25.140
And for hosting us here in Milan.
-Thank you as well.

00:01:28.380 --> 00:01:33.227
Right at the beginning,
we must explain our viewers

00:01:33.367 --> 00:01:36.290
our show is watched all over the world.
The show is global.

00:01:36.586 --> 00:01:40.219
When I say that, I mean the number
of guests and the careers they have had.

00:01:42.571 --> 00:01:46.430
We had Modrić, Đoković,
Ivanišević, Janica Kostelić,

00:01:46.571 --> 00:01:48.945
and all of them are global stars.

00:01:49.591 --> 00:01:52.727
However, the concept of the show
is more intended for viewers

00:01:52.845 --> 00:01:56.235
who live in "our region".

00:01:56.519 --> 00:02:03.439
That is our priority. The show will be
subtitled. -That will be necessary.

00:02:04.020 --> 00:02:08.740
However, it would be great
if we tried to talk in a language

00:02:09.020 --> 00:02:13.980
that people from that region understand.
Whatever you call that language. -Excellent.

00:02:14.180 --> 00:02:18.620
Congratulations on that,
because that is also one of the proofs

00:02:18.860 --> 00:02:22.580
of your greatness and courage,
that you decide to do it that way.

00:02:22.717 --> 00:02:25.157
All right. We'll try that first,
and if we don't succeed,

00:02:25.257 --> 00:02:27.657
then we'll talk in Swedish,
English, Italian...

00:02:27.740 --> 00:02:29.960
In Swedish we won't really
be able to talk.

00:02:30.084 --> 00:02:32.460
We just need subtitles.

00:02:35.420 --> 00:02:40.700
After your career, and you played
as long as you could. -That's right.

00:02:40.980 --> 00:02:44.260
You played as long as your knees
served you. -That's right.

00:02:44.580 --> 00:02:48.798
You played for a long time, and after
a career that was truly incredible,

00:02:48.962 --> 00:02:52.860
you became a personal advisor
to the club's owner.

00:02:53.260 --> 00:02:57.591
It's clear that you stayed
in the world of football,

00:02:57.739 --> 00:03:02.734
but does it compensate for the adrenaline,
the pressure and responsibility you had

00:03:02.796 --> 00:03:05.515
when you were a professional player?

00:03:06.740 --> 00:03:09.300
What I'm doing now
or when I was a player? -Yes.

00:03:10.260 --> 00:03:19.621
Everything I experienced as a player,
helped me become a good person.

00:03:21.541 --> 00:03:26.740
Everything I learned
and the environment I was in,

00:03:27.506 --> 00:03:39.992
all the people around me, players,
and those who weren't.

00:03:42.085 --> 00:03:47.813
That mentality of a winner
and that discipline that I had

00:03:48.156 --> 00:03:52.317
All of that helped me to become who I am.
And to always look forward.

00:03:52.493 --> 00:03:55.497
when I was a player,
I now use for other things.

00:03:55.631 --> 00:03:58.747
Whatever I do,
my goal is always to win.

00:03:58.854 --> 00:04:01.278
I've always thought that way.

00:04:01.393 --> 00:04:03.511
I don't want to say that
I don't know how to lose.

00:04:03.634 --> 00:04:05.770
Of course, there were
situations when I lost.

00:04:05.920 --> 00:04:14.064
I know how to handle defeat,
but that's not in my nature. -I understand.

00:04:14.250 --> 00:04:16.861
I always think that I must win,
that I want to win,

00:04:17.051 --> 00:04:20.421
and I know how I'm going to do it.
That's just how I am.

00:04:20.771 --> 00:04:25.265
Everything I do in life, I don't
do it the way most people would.

00:04:27.270 --> 00:04:31.598
I always want to be the best. -You want
to get the most out of yourself.

00:04:31.798 --> 00:04:36.512
Anything other than winning
means nothing to me.

00:04:36.762 --> 00:04:42.051
It doesn't fulfill me.
I just want to be different.

00:04:42.406 --> 00:04:46.043
Special. -If I am different from
others, then I am the best.

00:04:46.158 --> 00:04:48.536
That's just how I think.

00:04:48.654 --> 00:04:51.840
And I'm not talking only about football,
but about everything else I do.

00:04:51.943 --> 00:04:54.504
Whether it's investments,
different projects...

00:04:54.653 --> 00:04:57.269
Whatever I do,
I always behave the same way.

00:04:57.515 --> 00:05:02.404
You were the protagonist
on the field, the main character.

00:05:03.271 --> 00:05:05.676
There are many functions in football.

00:05:05.863 --> 00:05:10.044
I mean the directors,
coaches, advisors, etc.

00:05:10.418 --> 00:05:13.566
In my opinion, and I tried to work
in all these positions.

00:05:13.708 --> 00:05:21.435
Only the role of coach fulfills a person
as much as being a player.

00:05:21.667 --> 00:05:23.667
It's hard to talk about...

00:05:23.860 --> 00:05:26.940
And you said you didn't want to be
a coach, right? -I didn't.

00:05:28.100 --> 00:05:33.540
My opinion is that when a football player
reaches his maximum,

00:05:34.180 --> 00:05:38.185
it's very hard to reach that
same level as a coach.

00:05:38.459 --> 00:05:41.139
Coaching is something
completely different.

00:05:41.308 --> 00:05:44.302
In coaching, it might help you a bit
if you were a good player. -Yes.

00:05:44.529 --> 00:05:47.951
Because it is a completely
different kind of job.

00:05:48.158 --> 00:05:52.755
Many players make the mistake
of thinking that being good player

00:05:52.989 --> 00:05:59.021
will help them in the coaching career.
It's a completely different situation.

00:06:00.900 --> 00:06:10.020
It's very difficult for me right now that
I can't be a professional player anymore.

00:06:10.260 --> 00:06:14.100
That I can't help my colleagues anymore
and that I can't achieve good results.

00:06:14.340 --> 00:06:16.980
That I can't contribute to win.

00:06:17.220 --> 00:06:19.620
While I was playing football,
I felt somehow alive.

00:06:19.820 --> 00:06:21.740
That was my world.

00:06:21.940 --> 00:06:24.660
When he went out on the field,
I always had this feeling

00:06:24.860 --> 00:06:26.740
that only one can be a winner.

00:06:26.980 --> 00:06:29.460
I'll do everything to win,
but if you also want to win,

00:06:29.660 --> 00:06:32.300
you'll really have to work
hard to achive it.

00:06:32.460 --> 00:06:36.740
It can also happen that you win,
because I'm just an ordinary player too.

00:06:36.940 --> 00:06:44.620
Whenever I go out on the field, I only
think about the fact that I have to win.

00:06:44.820 --> 00:06:50.900
If I don't win, I feel as I'm not alive.
That's how I've always behaved.

00:06:51.466 --> 00:06:56.586
Now, while working in this position,
it is very hard for me that I can't

00:06:57.020 --> 00:07:03.700
help my players, the coach,
the fans, the club.

00:07:05.300 --> 00:07:12.100
I am currently learning how
to help them in a different way.

00:07:12.369 --> 00:07:15.149
However, it's very difficult for me.

00:07:15.249 --> 00:07:18.719
Because it's not the same job
I've been doing for the past 25 years.

00:07:18.897 --> 00:07:20.777
The situation is as it is.

00:07:20.914 --> 00:07:25.298
Now I have to help them
in a different way.

00:07:26.740 --> 00:07:31.180
I'm always there and I am growing.
When a player wants to become a coach,

00:07:31.540 --> 00:07:37.260
he has to start from the very beginning.
And he has to progress slowly.

00:07:37.469 --> 00:07:41.606
You're right, but that's hard to achieve.
You can's start from zero if you are...

00:07:41.820 --> 00:07:45.940
The problem is person's ego.

00:07:46.580 --> 00:07:49.780
And then he wants to be a coach
at a club that plays at the highest level.

00:07:50.020 --> 00:07:54.220
That's the biggest mistake someone
can make. -You're thinking correctly.

00:07:54.420 --> 00:07:58.660
Because if you make a mistake at such
a high level, there will be consequences.

00:07:58.900 --> 00:08:03.481
And if you start your coaching
career at a smaller club,

00:08:03.580 --> 00:08:06.294
then the consequences aren't the same.

00:08:06.470 --> 00:08:09.230
The damage isn't same as when
you're coaching a big club.

00:08:09.322 --> 00:08:13.465
When you make mistakes,
they follow you later.

00:08:13.598 --> 00:08:16.815
And when they look for you,
they see what happened.

00:08:16.981 --> 00:08:19.900
And when you start your career
at a club that plays at a lower level,

00:08:20.045 --> 00:08:24.094
there's room for mistakes. That's where
you should be making mistakes.

00:08:24.203 --> 00:08:26.837
And a person always learns more
while making mistakes

00:08:26.949 --> 00:08:29.977
than when everything is going well.
And a person needs to make mistakes.

00:08:31.400 --> 00:08:34.880
When I say you should
start from zero...

00:08:36.300 --> 00:08:40.020
If I ever wanted to become a coach,
I would first coach children.

00:08:40.165 --> 00:08:43.925
That's difficult. -I think that's
very difficult, because of person's ego.

00:08:44.062 --> 00:08:46.742
It takes a lot of time. -Then you start
wondering why you need

00:08:46.833 --> 00:08:50.040
that when you can immediately
start coaching professionals.

00:08:50.199 --> 00:08:52.438
It's not a problem to start
coaching professionals right away.

00:08:52.571 --> 00:08:54.811
If you are a well-known name
in the world of football,

00:08:54.923 --> 00:08:56.803
he'll be accepted immediately.

00:08:56.939 --> 00:09:00.595
However, the problem is when
you start making mistakes.

00:09:00.733 --> 00:09:04.165
Because of those mistakes,
it will become harder and harder

00:09:04.296 --> 00:09:06.048
for you to work later on.

00:09:06.151 --> 00:09:09.350
Many have made this mistake,
despite being good players.

00:09:10.866 --> 00:09:15.567
Today there are coaches and managers.

00:09:17.176 --> 00:09:21.169
In a big club and with a strong team,
it isn't difficult to work,

00:09:21.252 --> 00:09:23.360
although many people think it is.

00:09:23.525 --> 00:09:27.189
Personally, it isn't difficult for me
because I played for the biggest clubs

00:09:27.329 --> 00:09:29.603
and with the best players.

00:09:30.230 --> 00:09:39.975
You only need to motivate
the players in the starting eleven.

00:09:40.560 --> 00:09:44.439
You don’t need to tell them
how to move left or right.

00:09:44.861 --> 00:09:48.368
That’s how things are done in a big club
where the best players play.

00:09:48.504 --> 00:09:53.264
In smaller clubs, more work is needed
because they don't play at a high level.

00:09:53.780 --> 00:09:59.060
Many coaches today want to change
the style of play in order to bring

00:09:59.340 --> 00:10:03.500
something new into football
and to give themselves the main role.

00:10:03.686 --> 00:10:07.326
However, it’s the players who are
on the pitch and who actually play.

00:10:07.433 --> 00:10:09.753
You are right, football
is going in that direction.

00:10:10.740 --> 00:10:15.300
Today we have coaches who are
managers and who talk to the players

00:10:15.500 --> 00:10:19.140
as if they were friends.
They have a good relationship.

00:10:19.580 --> 00:10:23.020
And we also have coaches
who overthink too much

00:10:23.260 --> 00:10:26.740
and tell players how they should
move on the pitch.

00:10:26.940 --> 00:10:30.100
In a way, they try to "program" them.

00:10:30.340 --> 00:10:34.173
If everything is programmed...
-Yes, I know what you mean.

00:10:34.336 --> 00:10:37.204
Then you don't need good players.
Anyone can play like that.

00:10:37.302 --> 00:10:43.025
But you played... all your clubs
after Malmö's were big clubs.

00:10:43.405 --> 00:10:46.965
In such clubs, what’s really
needed is someone to lead

00:10:47.183 --> 00:10:52.663
a group of players, rather than
a coach who teaches them. -Exactly.

00:10:52.863 --> 00:11:00.217
Now that you're a director,
can you compare Zlatan as a director

00:11:00.354 --> 00:11:02.834
and Zlatan as a player?

00:11:03.900 --> 00:11:10.180
I’m the same. The way I was as a player,
that’s how I am as a director.

00:11:11.050 --> 00:11:17.119
However, now I look at football
from other side. -Yes.

00:11:17.440 --> 00:11:23.377
I used to ask myself why we
didn’t do certain things differently.

00:11:23.514 --> 00:11:27.314
However, I didn’t have
an answer to that question.

00:11:28.746 --> 00:11:33.408
Only now do I understand why we
couldn't do some things differently.

00:11:34.158 --> 00:11:38.877
Now the whole situation
is clear to me. -That’s right.

00:11:39.587 --> 00:11:43.580
Now it’s not just about your centre-forward
position, but about the whole club.

00:11:43.741 --> 00:11:46.104
I used to ask myself why we
didn’t do many things differently.

00:11:46.314 --> 00:11:50.765
However, for the
club to function well...

00:11:51.622 --> 00:11:54.309
A club is like a... -Company.

00:11:54.811 --> 00:11:59.914
In order to be able to buy players,
we first have to earn money.

00:12:00.250 --> 00:12:09.078
Sponsors are important, television rights.
-Yes, television rights.

00:12:09.200 --> 00:12:12.195
So that viewers can watch the matches.

00:12:12.390 --> 00:12:21.076
Every day I learn something new.
-But you’ve still remained humble.

00:12:21.800 --> 00:12:25.520
I’m not rushing too much.
-You simply listen and learn.

00:12:25.671 --> 00:12:31.251
I learn from professionals
from different categories.

00:12:31.783 --> 00:12:36.760
However, when it comes to the game itself,
that’s where I can help much more.

00:12:36.880 --> 00:12:39.158
What I know better
I can talk more about.

00:12:40.333 --> 00:12:44.190
These are two completely
different situations.

00:12:44.344 --> 00:12:47.173
You have two components,
and one of them is more familiar to you.

00:12:47.341 --> 00:12:50.141
However, you’re aware that it’s not
just about the game,

00:12:50.396 --> 00:12:54.255
but also about business.
-I'm trying to combine...

00:12:54.382 --> 00:12:57.262
You know the game on the field,
and you are trying to learn the rest.

00:12:57.377 --> 00:12:59.119
That’s how I would behave
if I were a coach as well.

00:12:59.266 --> 00:13:01.011
My ego didn't get the better of me.

00:13:01.174 --> 00:13:05.090
I never said because I was a famous
player that everything had to be my way.

00:13:07.968 --> 00:13:11.010
When I started working as a director,
I decided to observe and learn.

00:13:11.215 --> 00:13:17.389
I ask a lot of questions to learn
more and take it step by step.

00:13:17.551 --> 00:13:21.323
You need to approach it as a coach,
going step by step to make progress,

00:13:21.508 --> 00:13:25.173
and after that... A coach's career
is not the same as a player's,

00:13:25.220 --> 00:13:28.460
which lasts 10 to 20 years,
depending on how long a player plays.

00:13:28.780 --> 00:13:34.540
I believe that the more experience
a coach has, the better they become.

00:13:34.820 --> 00:13:37.220
There will be situations
where you're under stress,

00:13:37.460 --> 00:13:40.700
when things don't go as planned...

00:13:41.060 --> 00:13:46.900
At those moments,
it's not about how smart you are,

00:13:47.140 --> 00:13:50.660
but how much experience
you have, how you behave,

00:13:50.940 --> 00:13:55.500
and how you control the situation...
-How do you react to that...

00:13:55.940 --> 00:14:01.980
That's the most important thing,
but people think it's some kind of science.

00:14:03.312 --> 00:14:05.672
Everyone wants to be part of football.

00:14:05.920 --> 00:14:09.400
Everyone wants to reinvent football...
-They want to invent something new...

00:14:09.820 --> 00:14:13.660
I was a player, and you were too.
Anyone who's played football knows

00:14:13.900 --> 00:14:17.460
that if they played 50 years ago,
they'd still know how to play today.

00:14:17.700 --> 00:14:24.662
Nothing has changed. Today, the game
is just faster; modern players are perhaps

00:14:24.811 --> 00:14:29.780
bigger athletes; every player,
in my opinion, is an athlete;

00:14:30.220 --> 00:14:33.300
and one thing that has changed
is the tactics.

00:14:33.500 --> 00:14:38.180
It used to be about playing
with a sweeper, a 4-4-2;

00:14:38.460 --> 00:14:41.220
now it's more of a 4-3-3;

00:14:41.420 --> 00:14:45.285
now it's shifting towards having
more than 3 players in the back.

00:14:45.450 --> 00:14:48.610
That really depends on how the coach
wants the game to be played. -Exactly.

00:14:48.758 --> 00:14:51.316
That's changed, and that's okay,
but the way football is played,

00:14:51.473 --> 00:14:53.553
that's not something
that needs to be changed.

00:14:53.720 --> 00:14:56.231
Every player has their own
quality and character,

00:14:56.339 --> 00:14:59.179
and from that, you need to form a team.
That's it. -That's the secret, yes.

00:14:59.427 --> 00:15:03.142
The thing is, everyone wants to be part
of football because there's a lot...

00:15:03.317 --> 00:15:06.196
There's money, fame, and power.
-Football, football...

00:15:06.305 --> 00:15:10.905
But it's fantastic for you
that you're basically patient.

00:15:11.306 --> 00:15:13.866
You're humble and patient. -Very.

00:15:14.137 --> 00:15:18.525
You're patient, and as you said,
you take it step by step.

00:15:18.671 --> 00:15:22.626
Step by step. But when I played,
I was different.

00:15:22.861 --> 00:15:25.421
Back then, you thought, "Give everything,
and give it to me now."

00:15:26.220 --> 00:15:32.020
Back then, I was full of energy.
No one could stop me.

00:15:32.220 --> 00:15:35.878
They couldn't stop me.
I just moved forward.

00:15:36.253 --> 00:15:42.420
If I had to go through a wall, I would.
-Through the wall, yes.

00:15:43.213 --> 00:15:47.453
The way I grew up in Sweden,
everyone was kind of against me,

00:15:47.755 --> 00:15:54.366
and that stayed with me.
It shaped me into who I am today.

00:15:54.980 --> 00:15:59.940
Let's go back to the moment
when you mentioned 1981, Rosengård.

00:16:00.340 --> 00:16:06.822
It's part of Malmö, which was called
a ghetto, a multicultural ghetto

00:16:06.976 --> 00:16:13.016
full of foreigners. When you talk,
as I've seen in podcasts,

00:16:13.540 --> 00:16:17.020
you don't hide that it was difficult,

00:16:17.260 --> 00:16:22.540
and you speak of it with a sense of pride.
You're proud of it. -Very.

00:16:22.646 --> 00:16:25.926
You're proud of how it was for you.

00:16:26.143 --> 00:16:30.255
Actually, you mentioned that when they
asked you to describe it in three words,

00:16:30.508 --> 00:16:37.468
you said it was hard, suffering,
and sacrifice. Tell us more about that.

00:16:38.980 --> 00:16:43.620
I was born in Malmö,
in a small part called Rosengård,

00:16:43.980 --> 00:16:48.820
which they call a ghetto, but for me
it wasn't a ghetto, it was my life.

00:16:49.380 --> 00:16:55.380
I had everything I wanted; I didn't know
what it was like on the "other side."

00:16:55.620 --> 00:17:02.740
We lived here and played.
It was a multicultural neighborhood,

00:17:02.940 --> 00:17:07.900
with people from Africa, Asia, Europe...
we were all here, together.

00:17:09.980 --> 00:17:13.940
My father is from Bosnia,
from Bijeljina, a Muslim...

00:17:14.101 --> 00:17:18.351
And mother Jurka is Catholic.
-My mother is Catholic, from Zadar.

00:17:18.505 --> 00:17:20.185
I was born in Sweden.

00:17:20.980 --> 00:17:24.766
This is where I grew up
and played football,

00:17:25.025 --> 00:17:30.500
and up until I was 16 or 17,
I had never visited the center of Malmö.

00:17:30.726 --> 00:17:34.571
How is that possible? I read that.
-I was just in Rosengård. -Never?

00:17:34.672 --> 00:17:36.664
Never, until then,
had I been to the city center.

00:17:36.751 --> 00:17:39.118
And the center is close by,
20 minutes by bike.

00:17:39.328 --> 00:17:44.608
Everything was in Rosengård for me,
school, football, home, mom and dad,

00:17:44.700 --> 00:17:50.980
it was all here. We weren't in the city.
I didn't have a reason to go to the city.

00:17:51.220 --> 00:17:58.140
I never went on a school field trip
to the city center. Never.

00:17:59.980 --> 00:18:04.940
It's not a secret anymore,
but I stole a lot of bikes as a kid

00:18:05.140 --> 00:18:11.780
to get to practice. I didn't ride buses.
I didn't have money for a ticket.

00:18:12.554 --> 00:18:20.748
Either I walked or ran to practice
and school, or I'd steal a bike to go.

00:18:21.004 --> 00:18:23.779
Everything was here, my whole world.

00:18:23.990 --> 00:18:31.646
When I was 16, I went to the city
because a friend invited me.

00:18:31.764 --> 00:18:35.094
I asked him, "Which city?"
And he said, "The city center, Malmö."

00:18:35.271 --> 00:18:36.991
I said, "Okay, let's go."

00:18:37.131 --> 00:18:44.771
That was the first time I got on
the green bus, and in Sweden,

00:18:45.300 --> 00:18:48.500
those green buses take you everywhere.

00:18:48.694 --> 00:18:54.214
The first time I got on that bus,
I went to the city center.

00:18:54.460 --> 00:18:57.300
In Sweden, everyone is blue-eyed...

00:18:57.540 --> 00:19:04.139
I couldn't believe people looked like
that in the place where I lived,

00:19:04.420 --> 00:19:09.580
where I grew up, because I had never
seen the real Sweden before,

00:19:09.860 --> 00:19:12.580
I was surrounded by foreigners.

00:19:12.860 --> 00:19:16.980
At that moment, it was as if
a whole new world opened up to me.

00:19:17.180 --> 00:19:20.140
I wasn't yet playing for Malmö,
I was playing for smaller clubs,

00:19:20.380 --> 00:19:24.580
Balkan and MBE.
Those were two small clubs.

00:19:24.860 --> 00:19:29.260
I realized there was so much more
than what I had seen before.

00:19:29.700 --> 00:19:35.380
During that time, I went for a trial
at Malmö, and within two days,

00:19:35.620 --> 00:19:47.860
they told me to come play for them.
I was 17 or 18 when I started high school,

00:19:48.380 --> 00:19:52.860
actually grammar school. But that grammar
school wasn't in Rosengård,

00:19:53.060 --> 00:19:57.580
it was in the city. From then on,
I took the bus every day,

00:19:57.820 --> 00:20:00.020
back and forth from school and training.

00:20:00.260 --> 00:20:07.973
I still stole bikes because I didn't always
have money for bus tickets.

00:20:08.980 --> 00:20:14.460
That was when many doors opened up
for me, in life and in football.

00:20:14.700 --> 00:20:17.820
In Malmö, there was more...

00:20:18.060 --> 00:20:20.020
Well, when you play at home,
you play in Malmö.

00:20:20.260 --> 00:20:24.540
When we played in Rosengård,
there were games, training...

00:20:24.740 --> 00:20:28.300
Yes, yes, everything was local. -But with
Malmö, you go outside of Malmö.

00:20:28.540 --> 00:20:37.660
I visited smaller villages. -Suburbs...
-Smaller villages than Malmö and such.

00:20:38.100 --> 00:20:47.180
That's where I...
As a person, actually a young man...

00:20:47.460 --> 00:20:52.021
You built yourself as a person then...
-I was a wild child.

00:20:52.185 --> 00:20:56.905
Maybe a bit aggressive.
-Aggressive because of my family.

00:20:57.341 --> 00:21:02.700
I can't speak for all of the Balkans,
but in my family,

00:21:02.951 --> 00:21:07.031
we didn't really hug much,
we had a colder relationship.

00:21:08.946 --> 00:21:13.110
That's how they showed...
-Old school...

00:21:13.660 --> 00:21:17.460
Old school showing love
in an aggressive way.

00:21:17.637 --> 00:21:21.060
That was also how I showed
emotions toward others.

00:21:21.267 --> 00:21:25.667
When I played, I had a lot of
problems because of that.

00:21:26.353 --> 00:21:32.833
When I yelled at players on the field,
it seemed too aggressive, but...

00:21:33.260 --> 00:21:35.700
For you, that was normal.
-It was normal for me.

00:21:35.868 --> 00:21:41.958
They said I wasn't okay and that I wasn't
a good example for others,

00:21:42.231 --> 00:21:44.740
especially when the games
were shown on TV.

00:21:45.041 --> 00:21:51.267
Because of them, I felt like... They
made me feel like I was different.

00:21:51.861 --> 00:21:57.460
Like I was different from everyone...
That made me angry.

00:21:57.582 --> 00:21:59.782
For me, it was all normal.

00:21:59.952 --> 00:22:03.912
When I came home, we didn't say,
"Please, give me Coca-Cola."

00:22:04.190 --> 00:22:09.710
We just said, "Give me that Coca-Cola."
We had a different attitude.

00:22:09.832 --> 00:22:11.992
A different attitude, of course.
A different way...

00:22:12.139 --> 00:22:19.227
For them, it was different, like for
Swedes, they didn't understand that.

00:22:19.461 --> 00:22:25.218
You didn't fit into their framework.
-They didn't see me as Swedish.

00:22:25.405 --> 00:22:29.421
But I saw myself as Swedish,
and that's where the problem arose.

00:22:29.659 --> 00:22:35.819
For me and the people and me, I grew up
with and me, it was all normal.

00:22:36.232 --> 00:22:39.623
Yes, it's just a different way,
a different upbringing.

00:22:39.975 --> 00:22:51.015
That bothered me because I don't
want anyone to ever feel different.

00:22:51.420 --> 00:22:55.020
Everyone wants to feel normal.

00:22:55.260 --> 00:23:00.260
I'm not asking to feel like Superman,
or less worthy. -Yes, no one is special.

00:23:00.580 --> 00:23:06.900
Because of those people, I felt like
I was different, and that bothered me.

00:23:07.180 --> 00:23:14.540
I came there with a big nose,
brown hair, and 1.9 meters tall,

00:23:14.820 --> 00:23:20.740
while everyone else had
blue eyes and blonde hair.

00:23:20.940 --> 00:23:24.100
That was in Malmö, not Rosengård.

00:23:24.860 --> 00:23:28.774
I didn't even speak like all those guys,
I spoke with a dialect...

00:23:28.909 --> 00:23:30.869
You were different from them.

00:23:31.008 --> 00:23:33.608
I was pretty different in that sense,
but I felt normal.

00:23:33.800 --> 00:23:38.352
It was hard to accept
that I wasn't different,

00:23:38.541 --> 00:23:41.141
but that I was the same as them.

00:23:41.460 --> 00:23:49.342
At Malmö, there weren't many
foreign players at first.

00:23:49.653 --> 00:23:53.133
I opened the doors for everyone...

00:23:55.966 --> 00:23:59.046
For all those with
the same background as you...

00:23:59.420 --> 00:24:03.700
In essence, you were the first
to open the path for all.

00:24:03.940 --> 00:24:08.100
I opened the door for the opportunity,
but it's up to them to step through it.

00:24:08.340 --> 00:24:12.300
I opened the door for you,
but it's on you to take action.

00:24:12.540 --> 00:24:20.220
That's what I'm most proud of
from my time in Sweden.

00:24:20.473 --> 00:24:23.129
The fact that you opened
the doors for foreigners...

00:24:23.291 --> 00:24:26.931
That was important to me. I felt
different, and I don't want anyone

00:24:27.420 --> 00:24:31.180
from future generations to feel different.
That was important to me,

00:24:31.380 --> 00:24:35.500
and I'm more proud of that, even more
than football, from my time in Sweden.

00:24:35.980 --> 00:24:38.740
You carry all of that from home, right?

00:24:39.398 --> 00:24:42.383
You mentioned that your mom,
Jurka, was a cleaner,

00:24:42.592 --> 00:24:51.534
and you remember her as a hard worker.
-She worked every day, cleaning offices.

00:24:53.779 --> 00:24:58.259
My dad did various jobs
to maintain the city.

00:24:58.758 --> 00:25:03.061
If there was any plumbing problem,
he would fix it...

00:25:03.260 --> 00:25:06.331
He fixed things. It was
some kind of construction work...

00:25:06.620 --> 00:25:10.890
Whenever there was a problem,
he was available to fix it.

00:25:11.016 --> 00:25:13.702
He also used to sing, didn't he?
-Yes, he sang.

00:25:14.711 --> 00:25:22.863
It was like that. I often spent time alone.
When my dad was working,

00:25:23.340 --> 00:25:30.582
he couldn't be there for me. He couldn't
cook lunch at 1 PM or dinner at 7.

00:25:31.220 --> 00:25:35.740
My parents weren't together. I lived...
-You and Sanela, your sister?

00:25:35.980 --> 00:25:41.460
Sanela was with mom. My dad
couldn't cook meals every day.

00:25:42.060 --> 00:25:46.340
He would make Bolognese sauce
that we ate for seven days.

00:25:46.700 --> 00:25:52.900
I learned how to cook pasta and reheat
the Bolognese sauce we had for the week.

00:25:53.140 --> 00:25:58.300
For me, that was fine. I had something
to eat, I had bread and milk,

00:25:58.540 --> 00:26:01.587
and that was great for me.

00:26:01.843 --> 00:26:06.141
That's why I say it's easier
for my children today.

00:26:06.554 --> 00:26:11.462
They don't just have milk and bread;
they have many alternatives.

00:26:11.749 --> 00:26:16.029
My parents gave me
everything they could.

00:26:16.300 --> 00:26:22.140
That's why I say it was enough for me,
and I had everything I needed.

00:26:22.413 --> 00:26:28.320
I didn't know there were other things;
I only knew about this.

00:26:28.540 --> 00:26:31.110
That's why I say it was enough for me.

00:26:31.359 --> 00:26:35.151
I'm telling you, if I had known
there were other options,

00:26:35.340 --> 00:26:42.620
I wouldn't have asked for them. I was
raised to be grateful for what I had,

00:26:42.820 --> 00:26:45.460
and I've passed that on to my children.

00:26:45.660 --> 00:26:50.660
You must be grateful for what you have.
If you want more, you must work for it.

00:26:50.900 --> 00:26:56.580
You said that very well. Today’s
generations have a problem seeing all.

00:26:56.940 --> 00:27:01.980
Today it’s easy. -Everything is right
there, but it’s not. Not really.

00:27:02.220 --> 00:27:06.940
I can even touch it. Before you could
see everything, but not touch it.

00:27:07.220 --> 00:27:10.820
It was like a dream. -A dream.

00:27:11.060 --> 00:27:16.900
But it was better for it to stay a dream,
than for it to come true. -Bravo.

00:27:17.140 --> 00:27:20.140
You can’t lose your head
if it’s... -Unreachable.

00:27:20.460 --> 00:27:24.180
You say your father had
a big influence on you,

00:27:24.540 --> 00:27:29.980
that he never hit you and never had
to repeat himself twice... -Never.

00:27:30.260 --> 00:27:37.260
He was simply dedicated.
-He was... -He had presence.

00:27:37.540 --> 00:27:46.140
He was proud. The moment he looked
at me, I understood what it was about.

00:27:46.500 --> 00:27:55.020
He never hit me or slapped me.
He would just look at me. I made mistakes.

00:27:55.460 --> 00:28:01.740
We all make mistakes.
If you don’t make them, you won’t learn.

00:28:01.980 --> 00:28:10.377
When I made a mistake, you could see
he was the head of the house. -Of family.

00:28:12.700 --> 00:28:17.088
He was in charge. That’s how
I learned to be disciplined.

00:28:17.447 --> 00:28:21.367
If he said I should be home at 9,
it was 9. I was home.

00:28:21.709 --> 00:28:26.069
Nine and one minute, no.
Exactly at nine, I was home then.

00:28:26.457 --> 00:28:33.057
I wasn’t afraid of him, I understood
that at 9:01 there would be problems.

00:28:33.420 --> 00:28:37.740
Even though he never... -Never.
I was very disciplined.

00:28:37.855 --> 00:28:40.564
That’s also a kind of respect.

00:28:43.260 --> 00:28:47.292
Like I already said,
maybe it was aggressive,

00:28:47.503 --> 00:28:53.839
but to me it was normal.
When I would go to my mom’s...

00:28:54.948 --> 00:29:01.675
She had three kids. Different.
Father had two. Older brother...

00:29:03.008 --> 00:29:10.956
I don’t know, maybe he grew up
one way, mom another way.

00:29:11.825 --> 00:29:18.831
I lived with him my whole life
until I signed a professional contract.

00:29:19.740 --> 00:29:27.660
There was discipline.
First rule... -Yes, rule.

00:29:28.060 --> 00:29:31.580
The first rule was discipline.
That was the most important.

00:29:31.780 --> 00:29:35.380
He would say that while he is there,
he decides the rules.

00:29:35.549 --> 00:29:38.189
When you leave this house,
do whatever you want.

00:29:38.350 --> 00:29:41.470
While you are in my house,
everything will be as I say.

00:29:41.860 --> 00:29:51.180
That’s how it was. -That’s how it
should be. That’s just gone today.

00:29:51.420 --> 00:29:55.180
That’s the old school... -Propper school.
-How it was done before. -Old school.

00:29:55.420 --> 00:30:00.100
I think it was harder before than today.
Like you said. You can see everything

00:30:00.340 --> 00:30:05.940
and touch it. Before, to do
certain things, like as a player,

00:30:06.140 --> 00:30:12.060
for people to know who you were,
you had to play big matches,

00:30:12.300 --> 00:30:18.380
at a famous stadium, to be on
television. Today it’s not like that.

00:30:18.660 --> 00:30:21.660
Today you go to training and the whole
world can get to know you

00:30:21.900 --> 00:30:28.580
through Instagram, TikTok... -YouTube.
-I don’t know if that helps or not.

00:30:28.780 --> 00:30:33.780
Before we had to prove
ourselves more, work more,

00:30:34.100 --> 00:30:38.700
we had to go through the path
to where we wanted to be.

00:30:39.020 --> 00:30:42.860
Today one 10-second TikTok
and the whole world knows who you are.

00:30:43.060 --> 00:30:46.900
That might open doors for you,
whether you’re good or not.

00:30:47.140 --> 00:30:55.340
That’s why I’m grateful I saw
the old school and today’s school.

00:30:55.638 --> 00:30:59.838
I saw both. -You saw both sides.
-The situation is different.

00:30:59.964 --> 00:31:06.927
Ithink one thing, another happens.
And that’s how everything is today, 2025.

00:31:07.100 --> 00:31:12.620
You have to adapt. -That’s right, adapt.
You can’t change the world.

00:31:12.980 --> 00:31:17.222
You are who you are and
must adapt to the system.

00:31:17.410 --> 00:31:21.490
That’s how it is today.
-You said that very well.

00:31:23.660 --> 00:31:31.665
During that growing up...
You were born in 1981. War happens.

00:31:31.994 --> 00:31:40.594
You were a teenager then, 12-13 years old.
Mother is Catholic, father Muslim.

00:31:40.991 --> 00:31:46.831
Were there disturbances in relationships,
not between them, but among boys

00:31:47.260 --> 00:31:52.460
you hung out with. -In the city
where I lived there were Croats,

00:31:52.740 --> 00:32:00.900
Serbs, Bosnians, Albanians,
all of them. We were all like one.

00:32:01.500 --> 00:32:09.980
It didn’t matter where you were from.
We respected each other. -When the war began.

00:32:10.380 --> 00:32:17.500
Then the war started. I wasn’t
at an age to read newspapers.

00:32:18.900 --> 00:32:26.660
I didn’t even have a phone. We had a TV
at home, but I didn’t follow the news.

00:32:27.220 --> 00:32:34.380
You’re a child. -What do I remember?
I remember my father was always calling.

00:32:34.660 --> 00:32:38.820
Talking, phone, phone.
He would tell me to go outside,

00:32:39.060 --> 00:32:43.460
that he had to talk on the phone.
In the end I realized he was talking

00:32:43.700 --> 00:32:49.540
with family in Bosnia... -In Bijeljina.
-To bring them to Sweden, to help them.

00:32:49.780 --> 00:32:52.220
He was always on the phone.

00:32:52.580 --> 00:33:00.060
Once I came to my mom’s place.
I ate more at mom’s. -Why?

00:33:00.380 --> 00:33:09.293
Father didn’t cook, mom did.
Mom cooked more than father.

00:33:09.466 --> 00:33:15.583
She kicked me out of the house saying
I ate for two or three people.

00:33:16.060 --> 00:33:20.700
It wasn’t enough. I played
football and had to eat more.

00:33:21.100 --> 00:33:28.060
I was more active. So she would kick me out.
-They lived close? -Close. Five minutes.

00:33:28.340 --> 00:33:37.340
They were always close... -Because of you?
-Yes. One day we came to mom’s place.

00:33:37.660 --> 00:33:44.940
I saw everyone dressed in black.
No one told me anything.

00:33:45.340 --> 00:33:50.260
I asked why they were wearing black.
They told me to go outside and play football.

00:33:50.500 --> 00:33:55.500
Why is everyone in black? They didn’t
want to tell me. Go play football.

00:33:58.180 --> 00:34:02.166
Grandmother died.

00:34:04.042 --> 00:34:08.091
A funeral was held.

00:34:08.760 --> 00:34:16.260
No one taught me the customs and
they didn’t allow me to go to the funeral.

00:34:16.620 --> 00:34:27.624
They always kept me aside.
To be that kid and do my own things.

00:34:27.999 --> 00:34:33.585
Maybe they wanted to protect you.
-That’s what I want to say.

00:34:33.886 --> 00:34:37.726
Father always kept me aside
and told me to go play football.

00:34:38.420 --> 00:34:44.700
When all that happened, they kept
me aside so I wouldn’t feel it.

00:34:45.340 --> 00:34:53.740
Another thing that happened was
that refugees came to Sweden.

00:34:54.260 --> 00:34:59.100
But they had a different mentality.
It was more like, I’m a Bosnian,

00:34:59.380 --> 00:35:08.500
you’re a Serb. And there were fewer Croats.
In Bosnia there were problems.

00:35:08.900 --> 00:35:15.957
When they came to that ghetto, Rosengård,
a different mentality took over.

00:35:16.157 --> 00:35:21.183
For me, Yugoslavia existed.
In my head it was still like that.

00:35:21.489 --> 00:35:26.449
War happened. I had friends who were
Serbs, Croats, Bosnians, Albanians.

00:35:26.800 --> 00:35:32.050
Those who came had a different...
-Mindset. -Yes. Very different.

00:35:32.300 --> 00:35:36.060
Were they hurt? -We fought with them.
-Did you? -Yes.

00:35:36.900 --> 00:35:41.700
They didn’t accept that such a situation
ruled. For us it was normal.

00:35:42.620 --> 00:35:46.900
They were young, different thinking.
For me it was different,

00:35:47.260 --> 00:35:55.340
because I didn’t have that mindset,
that we’re different or from other states.

00:35:55.780 --> 00:36:01.380
Wherever I went to play, I always
thought we were the same.

00:36:01.620 --> 00:36:08.060
That’s how I grew up and I didn’t feel
the war that much, because they protected me.

00:36:08.260 --> 00:36:13.940
That’s why I can’t say much about the war.
-I get it. -I’ve lived in Sweden all my life.

00:36:14.260 --> 00:36:21.060
I don’t have that... How do you say?
-You don’t have that charge.

00:36:21.260 --> 00:36:24.700
The war didn’t leave a mark on you.
Your family protected you.

00:36:24.940 --> 00:36:28.780
I don’t even have the right to talk
about it, because I wasn’t there.

00:36:29.020 --> 00:36:31.780
I grew up in Sweden.
I can speak our languages.

00:36:32.020 --> 00:36:35.660
My father is from Bosnia, Muslim,
my mother is Catholic from Zadar.

00:36:35.900 --> 00:36:43.140
I never felt that.
-They protected you. -Yes. 100%.

00:36:43.340 --> 00:36:46.340
You started playing football
at six years old, right? -Yes.

00:36:46.540 --> 00:36:52.260
First Balkan, then later Malmö.
You say football was your way out,

00:36:52.540 --> 00:36:58.013
your kind of salvation. -Yes.
-What about taekwondo? When did you train?

00:37:00.122 --> 00:37:05.300
You have a black belt, right?
-Yes. My father’s brother was a boxer.

00:37:05.523 --> 00:37:09.779
In Bosnia. -OK. -He had many
recordings of himself.

00:37:09.978 --> 00:37:16.378
He had many recordings of Muhammad Ali.
We used to have VHS tapes. -Yes.

00:37:16.860 --> 00:37:23.860
Today everything is digital. We had many
Bruce Lee and Jackie Chan movies.

00:37:24.140 --> 00:37:28.300
I would always watch them and he
would play those movies for me.

00:37:28.445 --> 00:37:32.980
Father and I watched them.
I watched the kicks and everything.

00:37:33.184 --> 00:37:38.767
But it was a movie.
I said I want to try this.

00:37:39.892 --> 00:37:43.395
I went to try taekwondo and I liked it.

00:37:43.848 --> 00:37:48.620
I wanted to train it.
I trained taekwondo and football.

00:37:48.980 --> 00:37:56.940
In the end, I don’t know if it helped
me while playing football or not.

00:37:57.220 --> 00:38:00.300
But that’s how I played.
-What kind of goals did you score?

00:38:00.580 --> 00:38:04.660
You couldn’t score goals like that.
-For me it was natural.

00:38:04.900 --> 00:38:08.740
To lift my leg like this and control
the ball or pass it. -But only for you.

00:38:08.901 --> 00:38:12.781
For no one else is that natural.
-I say it’s possible it helped me,

00:38:13.007 --> 00:38:18.127
because I had... How do you say?
-Agility. -I was 1.94 tall.

00:38:18.500 --> 00:38:23.100
That wasn’t normal. So when they
saw me, they would say that at 1.94

00:38:23.340 --> 00:38:30.260
I do things like someone 1.60, 1.70.
-That’s taekwondo. -It was different.

00:38:30.500 --> 00:38:37.180
Something new at that time. Today
all players are athletes, all are tall.

00:38:37.580 --> 00:38:43.109
Before they weren’t that tall.
They told me to play basketball.

00:38:45.460 --> 00:38:49.420
I only played football and that
was something new. -Yes.

00:38:49.940 --> 00:38:53.700
You said mom and dad lived
five minutes from each other. -Yes.

00:38:53.940 --> 00:38:59.500
There’s that famous story that
stayed with you your whole life,

00:38:59.780 --> 00:39:06.815
about the fridge at dad’s not having...
-Milk, bread and Bolognese. Three things.

00:39:09.260 --> 00:39:18.260
I tell my kids, if I could...
How do you say? -If you succeed.

00:39:18.540 --> 00:39:23.900
If someone succeeds with those three things,
then you can succeed too.

00:39:24.380 --> 00:39:31.340
How do they accept that? -OK. -OK?
-The way my parents raised me,

00:39:31.980 --> 00:39:35.820
that’s how I raise them.
-Just different circumstances, of course.

00:39:36.020 --> 00:39:42.180
We have different alternatives.
I have more money than my parents.

00:39:42.620 --> 00:39:50.340
I think life is easier with money.
It won’t give you... -Happiness. -Happiness.

00:39:50.580 --> 00:39:54.420
But things become easier. -Of course.
-It’s the same with them.

00:39:54.620 --> 00:40:01.660
I teach them discipline, respect
and... How do you say? -Independence.

00:40:01.933 --> 00:40:06.455
﻿If by the age of 18
they don't become independent,

00:40:06.568 --> 00:40:08.455
then I haven't succeeded in my job.

00:40:08.562 --> 00:40:10.744
But the most important things
are discipline and respect.

00:40:10.890 --> 00:40:15.267
I tell them: "If I managed with these
three things, then you can too."

00:40:15.386 --> 00:40:17.720
But not everyone has to be
Zlatan Ibrahimović.

00:40:17.821 --> 00:40:20.478
That's me, I can't speak on behalf
of others. -Not everyone is a monster.

00:40:20.541 --> 00:40:23.189
Not everyone is 195 cm tall,
nor does have such a strong mind.

00:40:23.319 --> 00:40:26.087
My children didn't have a phone
until they turned 13.

00:40:26.211 --> 00:40:28.411
Even today, they don't have
Instagram profiles.

00:40:28.565 --> 00:40:33.501
My older son has an Instagram profile,
but only through football.

00:40:34.407 --> 00:40:39.127
The younger one still doesn't have one,
but his time will come.

00:40:39.289 --> 00:40:43.189
When he starts playing football...
Actually, he already plays, but...

00:40:43.333 --> 00:40:46.259
When he gets registered.
-Yes, that. Then he can have it.

00:40:46.439 --> 00:40:50.439
Until the age of 14, they can't have
a private Instagram profile.

00:40:52.060 --> 00:40:55.500
When we were in Beverly Hills,
not to brag,

00:40:55.820 --> 00:41:00.500
but that's how I did it
when I played in Los Angeles...

00:41:00.780 --> 00:41:07.460
When they go to school, everyone
has a driver... -A whole entourage.

00:41:09.220 --> 00:41:14.020
There were only two bicycles in
front of the school, Vincent's and Maxi's.

00:41:14.220 --> 00:41:19.100
I bought two bicycles and told them,
"You're going to school on your own."

00:41:19.540 --> 00:41:24.180
I showed them how, and from that day
on they went by themselves.

00:41:24.620 --> 00:41:28.940
They were kind of funny one day
because it was raining.

00:41:29.180 --> 00:41:32.140
They asked what they were supposed
to do now, and I answered

00:41:32.380 --> 00:41:35.460
that they should take their
bikes and go. And they did.

00:41:35.700 --> 00:41:37.780
They thought they wouldn't
have to ride their bikes,

00:41:38.020 --> 00:41:43.980
at least when it was raining.
I was firm and strong.

00:41:46.260 --> 00:41:52.756
For their own good. -Yes, consistently.
-You didn't give up.

00:41:54.477 --> 00:41:57.557
It was a long-term decision.

00:41:58.060 --> 00:42:04.500
Maybe I isolated them too much from others,
but that was because of my situation.

00:42:05.020 --> 00:42:10.660
I was well-known, we lived well,
and I didn't want anything to happen to them.

00:42:11.660 --> 00:42:15.500
Little by little I eased up,
and now they go on their own.

00:42:15.740 --> 00:42:22.176
That's just how I am. -A fantastic example.
-And it's the same with my wife.

00:42:23.780 --> 00:42:28.710
When it comes to flying...
well, with me it's different.

00:42:28.850 --> 00:42:32.420
When I travel, I fly by private jet
so people don't bother me. -Yes.

00:42:32.561 --> 00:42:36.124
That's something completely different.
And the reason isn't that I have money.

00:42:36.265 --> 00:42:38.140
Or if you're in a hurry. -Yes.

00:42:38.321 --> 00:42:41.327
But when she travels,
she uses regular commercial flights.

00:42:41.408 --> 00:42:43.968
EasyJet, Ryanair, and so on.

00:42:44.099 --> 00:42:46.023
That's how she travels
with the children.

00:42:46.106 --> 00:42:50.186
She says they need to see what
the real world actually looks like.

00:42:50.307 --> 00:42:53.699
When you fly by private jet,
that just isn't possible.

00:42:54.260 --> 00:42:59.180
That was important to both of us.
But I have to say, they're very grateful.

00:42:59.500 --> 00:43:03.460
They don't ask for more than they have.
And that's why I always

00:43:03.700 --> 00:43:07.860
use this as an example: "If I could
do it-starting with nothing,

00:43:08.140 --> 00:43:11.860
become who I am today and achieve
what I have, then you can do it too.

00:43:12.180 --> 00:43:17.460
Because what you have today is
200 percent more than what I had.

00:43:17.700 --> 00:43:20.460
So if I could do it, you can too.

00:43:21.300 --> 00:43:24.060
I'm proof of that.
Is that the right way to say it?

00:43:24.260 --> 00:43:29.820
Yes, you are-the proof.
-That it's all possible. -Exactly.

00:43:31.380 --> 00:43:34.940
You're fine player in the FBK Balkan,
but basically, at seventeen

00:43:35.220 --> 00:43:37.860
you come to the city center
for the first time.

00:43:38.140 --> 00:43:41.580
You started high school.
You said you weren't a bad student.

00:43:41.780 --> 00:43:46.140
I was okay. I was disciplined.

00:43:46.340 --> 00:43:54.780
There, on the grading scale from 1 to 5,
where 5 was the highest grade, I was a 3.

00:43:55.300 --> 00:43:58.220
Like here-that's a "good."
-That was fine.

00:44:01.580 --> 00:44:06.061
Then, while I was in school,
I was afraid of making mistakes.

00:44:06.137 --> 00:44:08.577
That's something my father
instilled in me.

00:44:08.684 --> 00:44:11.604
If I made a mistake, I was afraid
something would happen.

00:44:11.718 --> 00:44:13.998
Fear of consequences?
-And that's what discipline was.

00:44:14.193 --> 00:44:16.593
You were responsible, basically.
-When he told me

00:44:16.770 --> 00:44:20.748
I had to be home by 9 PM,
I was afraid something would happen

00:44:20.839 --> 00:44:22.911
if I didn't come home
exactly at that time.

00:44:23.139 --> 00:44:28.279
The same thing happened at school.
That gave you a sense of responsibility. -Yes.

00:44:28.516 --> 00:44:30.916
It's one kind of discipline.

00:44:31.252 --> 00:44:34.452
I would be angry at myself
for not getting there earlier,

00:44:34.755 --> 00:44:39.233
because that's not in my character.
-That's a terrible thing.

00:44:40.895 --> 00:44:48.815
When we warm up at training,
there are white lines we run between.

00:44:49.220 --> 00:44:53.460
I touch every one when I reach it.
That's my discipline.

00:44:54.740 --> 00:44:57.180
Always? -Yes, always.

00:44:57.299 --> 00:44:59.387
That's my discipline...
-Even in training?

00:44:59.556 --> 00:45:02.533
Yes, because I was afraid
that if I didn't touch it,

00:45:02.666 --> 00:45:04.706
something is gonna happen.

00:45:04.961 --> 00:45:08.010
Because of that fear,
I always touched it.

00:45:08.164 --> 00:45:11.484
In the end I realized
that if I don't touch it,

00:45:12.860 --> 00:45:17.500
and if I steal a few meters,
I'm not stealing from you,

00:45:17.621 --> 00:45:19.451
I'm stealing from myself.

00:45:19.567 --> 00:45:22.640
I'm the one at a loss, no one else.
-That's intense.

00:45:22.817 --> 00:45:27.281
So, if I have to run 10 km, my mentality
and discipline tell me to run the full ten.

00:45:27.453 --> 00:45:31.960
If you, as my coach, say: "Ibra,
today we're running ten kilometers,"

00:45:32.940 --> 00:45:40.620
I won't run nine, or 9.5, or 10.1.
I'll give you the full ten.

00:45:40.860 --> 00:45:45.292
When I decide in my head it has to be ten,
I'll die if I have to-but it will be ten.

00:45:45.427 --> 00:45:46.987
That's my mentality.

00:45:47.329 --> 00:45:52.895
But wait... I read in a book
that you used to sneak onto buses

00:45:53.033 --> 00:45:55.193
and the thing with the bikes...
-When we stole bikes?

00:45:55.466 --> 00:45:58.626
It happened with a friend.
He brought me along and said,

00:45:58.835 --> 00:46:01.635
"Instead of running for a long time,
we'll just get on the bus

00:46:01.882 --> 00:46:06.202
and wait for them there."
Back then, I wasn't a professional.

00:46:06.614 --> 00:46:11.294
I didn't think about the consequences.
I wasn't scared.

00:46:11.564 --> 00:46:18.856
I was a bit wild. -Yeah.
-I'm going to tell you something now

00:46:19.066 --> 00:46:24.546
that nobody knows,
and it's a little awkward.

00:46:25.380 --> 00:46:30.300
When I came back after a knee injury,
after breaking both of them,

00:46:30.540 --> 00:46:33.980
I was running on a treadmill.

00:46:35.420 --> 00:46:45.909
The workout was six fast intervals,
two minutes each,

00:46:46.870 --> 00:46:50.846
with just three seconds of rest.
That was the pace.

00:46:51.119 --> 00:46:54.245
I was almost at the very end
when I suddenly felt the urge

00:46:54.421 --> 00:46:58.244
to go to the toilet.
But I didn't go to the toilet.

00:46:58.439 --> 00:47:05.247
While I was running, I literally
shat myself, but I kept running

00:47:05.580 --> 00:47:10.540
because in my head I had to finish
first and then go. -Come on...

00:47:10.860 --> 00:47:16.500
But that's who I am. I always said:
If I cheat, I cheat myself - not you.

00:47:17.340 --> 00:47:21.500
I'm the one who loses, not you.
-Respect. -That's me.

00:47:21.700 --> 00:47:25.700
Why did they assign you
a supervisor at school? That woman?

00:47:25.980 --> 00:47:29.220
They said I was different
from the others. That I was wild.

00:47:29.460 --> 00:47:31.540
And I didn't like that.

00:47:31.703 --> 00:47:35.183
I got angry and started
being aggressive toward her,

00:47:35.540 --> 00:47:41.780
even though it wasn't her fault.
They made me feel different.

00:47:42.220 --> 00:47:49.567
And that wasn't right for me.
Once, while we were playing,

00:47:50.240 --> 00:47:54.100
I grabbed her by the head.
That wasn't right either.

00:47:54.500 --> 00:47:57.580
I shouldn't have done that.
-Yeah. -It's just that they...

00:47:59.500 --> 00:48:04.580
The worst part is...
Now that I work in Milan,

00:48:04.860 --> 00:48:07.900
when I train with the kids
from the academy

00:48:08.220 --> 00:48:16.260
and I see that they behave differently,
I still treat them all the same.

00:48:16.460 --> 00:48:18.540
To me, everyone is equal.

00:48:18.780 --> 00:48:21.380
Later on, some of them
might turn out to be better,

00:48:21.660 --> 00:48:24.300
but I believe everyone
deserves the same chance.

00:48:24.540 --> 00:48:30.860
I don't know if you've seen the footage
from when I played in Paris,

00:48:31.140 --> 00:48:36.220
where they switched the kid
next to me on the field.

00:48:36.420 --> 00:48:39.700
Maybe the boy's father asked them
to put him beside me,

00:48:39.900 --> 00:48:42.860
because he thought
it was more important.

00:48:43.060 --> 00:48:47.260
But I said no.
"Go to the back, he stays here."

00:48:47.740 --> 00:48:51.940
In my world, no one is different.
Everyone is equal.

00:48:52.317 --> 00:48:58.054
We all have the same chance.
We're born with the same opportunities,

00:48:58.316 --> 00:49:01.867
and it's up to us
what we do with our lives.

00:49:02.030 --> 00:49:04.910
It depends on you.
-That's fairness, basically. Bravo.

00:49:05.010 --> 00:49:08.010
That's how I think,
that's how I was raised.

00:49:08.580 --> 00:49:11.460
And it's the same lesson
I want to pass on to others.

00:49:12.420 --> 00:49:17.100
So, Malmö... it's going well.
I mean, well in the academy.

00:49:17.380 --> 00:49:21.060
In Malmö, you had a problem with...
-Everyone seemed to be against me.

00:49:21.340 --> 00:49:28.202
They had already signed a contract,
but I was so good they couldn't

00:49:28.702 --> 00:49:34.380
get rid of me or block me.
I was just too good.

00:49:34.740 --> 00:49:40.180
In the end, I signed the contract
and took the first step

00:49:40.420 --> 00:49:43.220
toward the first team
and professional football.

00:49:43.420 --> 00:49:46.060
They realized who I was.

00:49:47.052 --> 00:49:53.294
190... Actually, back then I was 188 cm.
-You were still growing, you were young.

00:49:53.485 --> 00:49:56.085
I was skinny. -Slim. -Yeah, slim.

00:49:56.207 --> 00:50:00.687
When I was playing,
they could see I was different.

00:50:01.241 --> 00:50:08.310
They said, "We'll give him a chance."
And then everything exploded.

00:50:09.060 --> 00:50:11.300
Because I wasn't like the others.

00:50:11.580 --> 00:50:15.460
They said I was arrogant,
because, even back then, I would say

00:50:15.700 --> 00:50:18.260
that I was the best.
I would say there wasn't

00:50:18.500 --> 00:50:20.780
a single player in Sweden
who was better than me.

00:50:20.940 --> 00:50:24.020
And I was only 17 or 18.

00:50:24.300 --> 00:50:31.860
Even then, I had a lot of confidence
and I thought I was the best.

00:50:32.980 --> 00:50:37.300
I grew up in Rosengård,
where it was either me or them.

00:50:37.540 --> 00:50:41.420
Who would survive?
And that pushed me forward.

00:50:41.660 --> 00:50:44.740
But for them, it wasn't normal.

00:50:45.020 --> 00:50:49.300
In Sweden, equality is important.
-No gladiator fights.

00:50:49.540 --> 00:50:52.340
They watch everyone and say,
"What are you doing?"

00:50:52.580 --> 00:50:57.580
You arrive in a nice car
and immediately they ask,

00:50:57.820 --> 00:50:59.860
"Where did you get that?"

00:51:00.100 --> 00:51:03.660
And I had already told them
that I was the best of all,

00:51:03.900 --> 00:51:08.860
that there was no one better than me,
and they didn't like it. It bothered them.

00:51:09.140 --> 00:51:15.260
They said I was arrogant, a prima donna,
that I thought I was "something"...

00:51:15.500 --> 00:51:24.523
An individualist. -I believe that
if a person says he's smart, intelligent,

00:51:24.643 --> 00:51:29.763
it means he has confidence,
not arrogance.

00:51:37.184 --> 00:51:40.304
It's not arrogance, it's self-confidence.

00:51:40.464 --> 00:51:44.424
If I know who I am
and what I can do, I will do it.

00:51:44.605 --> 00:51:49.752
Yes, but you have to respect people.
-You have to respect what they think.

00:51:50.128 --> 00:51:54.166
But that wasn't the case there.
It was different.

00:51:54.607 --> 00:52:01.161
Many things weren't okay for them.
And I've always been myself.

00:52:02.075 --> 00:52:07.935
Even when I signed the contract
and became well-known, I stayed the same.

00:52:08.147 --> 00:52:12.147
If you ask people who've known me
for 20 years, they'll tell you:

00:52:12.547 --> 00:52:17.507
"He's the same as he was 20 years ago."
The only thing that's changed for me

00:52:18.060 --> 00:52:21.098
is my bank account
and that I became popular.

00:52:21.221 --> 00:52:23.542
But as a person,
I've always been the same.

00:52:23.696 --> 00:52:27.001
I promised myself that
I would never change for anyone.

00:52:27.102 --> 00:52:31.306
Maybe I paid a price for that,
and I never won the Ballon d'Or.

00:52:32.144 --> 00:52:35.984
Alright. -But we can talk about
that later. -We definitely will.

00:52:36.186 --> 00:52:39.666
Modrić won, but I could have won too.

00:52:39.882 --> 00:52:44.682
I could have had that "perfect image,"
but I wanted to stay true to myself.

00:52:44.929 --> 00:52:48.849
It all comes down to your behavior,
actually, to your perception of everything.

00:52:49.062 --> 00:52:58.154
Not everyone is okay with one person
saying and doing whatever they want.

00:52:58.273 --> 00:53:03.353
Yes, it's not accepted.
-It's not "mainstream."

00:53:09.740 --> 00:53:13.138
You said that people change
every five years.

00:53:14.171 --> 00:53:21.404
When you came to Malmö's academy at 17,
you faced resistance

00:53:21.750 --> 00:53:25.830
from both parents and players.
They said you were an individualist,

00:53:26.220 --> 00:53:29.060
that you only thought about yourself,
that you were arrogant,

00:53:29.260 --> 00:53:31.260
that you ignored them, and so on.

00:53:31.440 --> 00:53:34.680
They wanted to kick me out of the team
because I was aggressive.

00:53:34.966 --> 00:53:41.187
And later you... like Mourinho...
Let's say that's true...

00:53:41.413 --> 00:53:46.375
Later you turned into a fantastic leader,
with a mentality,

00:53:46.900 --> 00:53:51.157
that every coach would wish for,
with that kind of mindset.

00:53:51.343 --> 00:53:54.423
Mourinho said that you were
his extended arm. -Yes.

00:53:54.771 --> 00:53:59.611
That you were his "extended hand."
-Yes... -An extended arm on the pitch.

00:53:59.820 --> 00:54:05.642
A phenomenal thing. They even wrote
some kind of petition, didn't they?

00:54:05.820 --> 00:54:09.180
To get you expelled,
because you hit some kid?

00:54:09.380 --> 00:54:15.540
I injured my head because of him.
It was a moment in a duel.

00:54:15.820 --> 00:54:21.900
When things happen...
not in a second, but in a millimeter...

00:54:22.140 --> 00:54:25.940
How do you say it...?
-Emotions, feelings...

00:54:26.140 --> 00:54:30.300
And it didn't happen to me just once,
it happened a hundred times.

00:54:30.500 --> 00:54:37.660
The parents of that player tried to get me
kicked out of the team in Malmö.

00:54:37.900 --> 00:54:41.820
They wrote some... -A petition? -Yes.

00:54:42.540 --> 00:54:48.740
For everyone to sign it and to throw me
out of Malmö, out of the club.

00:54:49.620 --> 00:54:53.860
But the coach was a great man.
When he saw that petition...

00:54:54.217 --> 00:54:58.169
And when was supposed to sign it...
-He protected you? -He protected me.

00:54:58.369 --> 00:55:04.569
He said: "What is this? They're kids,
this happens." It should be a lesson.

00:55:06.940 --> 00:55:12.580
Today, if you want to be perfect
as a human being,

00:55:12.980 --> 00:55:17.020
you have to make the effort yourself
to become perfect.

00:55:17.260 --> 00:55:21.860
You make mistakes, you learn, you
make mistakes again and you learn.

00:55:22.140 --> 00:55:27.460
But when you take care of yourself,
then you are perfect. -Yes.

00:55:27.740 --> 00:55:32.300
Everyone looks for perfection,
for an image, a name,

00:55:32.540 --> 00:55:35.780
a perfect picture of themselves.
They want to be that,

00:55:36.020 --> 00:55:41.900
but my world doesn't work that way.
If you respect me, I will respect you.

00:55:42.100 --> 00:55:45.980
You are who you are.  -I don't ask you
to love me or hate me.

00:55:46.220 --> 00:55:50.940
That's your opinion and your choice.
I don't ask you about that,

00:55:51.140 --> 00:55:55.460
because if I ask about it,
I already make a mistake.

00:55:55.700 --> 00:55:59.420
If you like me, fine, if you don't,
that's fine too. Then respect comes.

00:55:59.565 --> 00:56:01.205
That's how it is.

00:56:01.416 --> 00:56:05.996
I've noticed that many
athletes want to be perfect.

00:56:07.159 --> 00:56:10.199
That doesn't work. Tiger Woods
wanted to be the most perfect,

00:56:10.478 --> 00:56:14.118
but what happened to him?
That's the problem. -Exactly.

00:56:14.319 --> 00:56:18.759
You have to work on yourself.
We will make mistakes and learn,

00:56:19.180 --> 00:56:23.180
because no one is perfect
or programmed. That's not right.

00:56:23.420 --> 00:56:27.340
You have to work on yourself,
but you also have your upbringing,

00:56:27.580 --> 00:56:30.180
what kind of person you are, what kind
of character you have, and all that.

00:56:30.420 --> 00:56:33.700
You have ups and downs,
on a daily basis. -That's all normal.

00:56:33.940 --> 00:56:37.580
There are moments when you make mistakes
and moments when things go well.

00:56:37.780 --> 00:56:42.900
That's why I always look to be on my own,
because then I have responsibility.

00:56:45.180 --> 00:56:48.340
I am an example to the new generation.

00:56:48.540 --> 00:56:53.860
I can't have flaws that they
would think are acceptable.

00:56:54.060 --> 00:56:56.500
You have a responsibility to be
a positive example? -Yes.

00:56:56.740 --> 00:56:59.340
But you have to give your best
and be in your comfort zone.

00:56:59.540 --> 00:57:03.900
If you're not in your comfort zone,
then it's hard, you're not living your life.

00:57:04.100 --> 00:57:06.500
You're living a life,
but it's not really you.

00:57:06.700 --> 00:57:09.700
I've noticed that there's
a lot of that in America.

00:57:09.900 --> 00:57:14.595
They look for a perfect image.
-Everyone is pretending.

00:57:14.691 --> 00:57:16.491
Basically, it's all an act...

00:57:16.691 --> 00:57:23.399
Twenty people around them to make
them perfect... That's a movie.

00:57:24.460 --> 00:57:34.460
Who were your idols in sports,
in life, and in football?

00:57:35.154 --> 00:57:38.954
At the beginning, it was Muhammad Ali.
-Because of your father?

00:57:39.092 --> 00:57:40.997
Yes, because of my father.

00:57:41.126 --> 00:57:45.006
I used to sit in front of the TV
and watch Muhammad Ali.

00:57:45.915 --> 00:57:49.355
Back then we watched
black-and-white videos on TV.

00:57:49.595 --> 00:57:52.235
I listened to the way he spoke.

00:57:52.444 --> 00:57:59.684
In Swedish schools, English
was taught in the fourth grade, right?

00:57:59.815 --> 00:58:01.495
Yes, in the fourth grade.

00:58:01.783 --> 00:58:07.431
I was seven or eight years old
then and I understood English.

00:58:08.087 --> 00:58:12.275
I listened to him speak.
He wasn't arrogant.

00:58:12.553 --> 00:58:15.633
He was confident,
that's a big difference.

00:58:15.756 --> 00:58:18.516
Everyone needs to understand that.

00:58:18.765 --> 00:58:22.455
Many people think he was arrogant,
but he wasn't, it was confidence.

00:58:22.568 --> 00:58:25.648
It's close. -No, it's confidence.

00:58:25.803 --> 00:58:29.323
The difference is that Muhammad
lived what he spoke.

00:58:29.694 --> 00:58:34.014
"Walk the walk and talk the talk".
-Exactly. That's the biggest difference.

00:58:34.168 --> 00:58:37.516
Some people talk, but their actions
don't match their words.

00:58:37.720 --> 00:58:41.141
That's arrogance, they don't understand.
That's a clown.

00:58:41.387 --> 00:58:47.884
The confident, one who spoke, showed it.
In my world, I thought...

00:58:50.500 --> 00:58:57.300
Rosengård, ghetto and all that.
I'll be confident like Muhammad.

00:58:57.500 --> 00:59:03.023
I'll show that I'm the best.
Not in other things, only in football.

00:59:03.492 --> 00:59:08.835
That was constantly on my mind.
I wanted to be an idol like him.

00:59:09.211 --> 00:59:12.773
I turned boxing into football.

00:59:13.082 --> 00:59:20.585
I started watching a lot of football.
And Ronaldo, the Brazilian, for me was...

00:59:22.540 --> 00:59:28.820
I always say, when you see
that player on the pitch,

00:59:29.020 --> 00:59:35.740
you should do what he does.
And that's it. He is the best player.

00:59:36.060 --> 00:59:40.500
He steps over the ball,
goes right, left and escapes.

00:59:40.740 --> 00:59:48.340
The next day on the pitch I try to do that.
When you copy another player, that's top.

00:59:48.860 --> 00:59:53.060
Everything else... we have great players
and we can do things in different ways,

00:59:53.340 --> 00:59:57.300
but when you copy another player,
that's the difference.

00:59:57.540 --> 01:00:02.820
That's top-level. He was that for me.
When he did the "elastico"... -Yes.

01:00:03.140 --> 01:00:07.300
At that time there was YouTube,
there wasn't TikTok, Instagram...

01:00:07.540 --> 01:00:11.940
So I had to go to the school library...

01:00:13.260 --> 01:00:17.900
I wasn't allowed to be there,
because I was supposed to be in class...

01:00:18.180 --> 01:00:20.900
Yes, in class. -But I didn't go to class.

01:00:21.180 --> 01:00:26.460
I went to the library to research
on YouTube how he did it.

01:00:26.740 --> 01:00:32.140
And I observe, I watch, hiding
so no one would see me...

01:00:32.420 --> 01:00:37.660
And I watch on YouTube how it's done.
I analyze it, slow it down, and...

01:00:37.900 --> 01:00:44.660
At training in Malmö, I try to do it.
In the end, I had my own style.

01:00:45.420 --> 01:00:49.580
So, with Muhammad Ali's confidence,
"you walk like you talk,"

01:00:49.820 --> 01:00:53.340
and then Ronaldo,
with all the things he did,

01:00:53.660 --> 01:00:58.460
that was my desire... to play like that.
I wanted to be like that. -Bravo!

01:00:59.580 --> 01:01:03.500
To finish with your childhood,

01:01:04.580 --> 01:01:07.572
and something that's more
an opinion than a question.

01:01:07.746 --> 01:01:09.923
I'd like you to tell me
something about this.

01:01:10.063 --> 01:01:14.748
All the guests on the show
come  from generations

01:01:14.910 --> 01:01:20.545
where nobody was excessively rich
or extremely poor.

01:01:21.079 --> 01:01:25.959
However, all of them had
extraordinary family support.

01:01:26.620 --> 01:01:33.260
Đoković, Janica Kostelić,
Ivanišević, Modrić, everyone...

01:01:33.460 --> 01:01:37.100
Karabatić, Džeko, Stanić...

01:01:38.540 --> 01:01:47.460
But you said that when you were little,
no one asked you:"How are you, Zlatan?"

01:01:47.820 --> 01:01:50.620
There was no one to help you
with homework,

01:01:50.860 --> 01:01:55.660
you weren't even allowed to cry,
if someone was rough with you.

01:01:57.020 --> 01:02:06.100
When all that happened around me,
it was such a... not panic...

01:02:06.380 --> 01:02:13.020
but a story about me... -A mess?
-Things were happening too fast.

01:02:13.300 --> 01:02:19.616
When journalists started talking
about me on TV, day after day,

01:02:20.296 --> 01:02:23.140
it was as if a bomb had exploded.

01:02:23.740 --> 01:02:28.140
Back then I was making mistakes,
they contacted me...

01:02:28.420 --> 01:02:32.620
At that time, everyone could contact me.
I answered questions and talked to them.

01:02:32.860 --> 01:02:35.540
If they were journalists,

01:02:35.780 --> 01:02:39.500
the next day everything
I said would be in the newspapers.

01:02:39.780 --> 01:02:44.660
During that period, the World Cup was
taking place. Sweden went to America.

01:02:44.830 --> 01:02:47.510
I said I would go together with the team
and that we would win the World Cup.

01:02:47.648 --> 01:02:50.113
The very next day,
it was in the newspapers.

01:02:50.293 --> 01:02:52.133
I was... -"In".

01:02:55.700 --> 01:03:00.900
It wasn't hard to reach me,
like it is today.

01:03:01.140 --> 01:03:05.020
Today, if someone were looking for me,
they would have to talk to a lot of people.

01:03:05.260 --> 01:03:08.980
Back then, everything was accessible.
A lot of things happened.

01:03:09.180 --> 01:03:14.140
At that time, paparazzi weren't
a common sight in Sweden,

01:03:14.270 --> 01:03:17.444
but because of me,
they started to appear.

01:03:17.643 --> 01:03:22.523
They began following me through
the streets or when I went to a restaurant.

01:03:22.898 --> 01:03:29.178
I asked Henrik Larsson what I should do
to calm the situation down,

01:03:29.740 --> 01:03:33.580
to get the paparazzi under control.
It became impossible,

01:03:33.726 --> 01:03:37.886
they followed me every day. At one point,
headlines appeared: "Zlatan fever."

01:03:38.077 --> 01:03:40.597
Zlatan fever like gold fever.

01:03:40.743 --> 01:03:45.063
Every day they talked about me,
in the newspapers, on TV...

01:03:45.780 --> 01:03:50.900
Back then, social media didn't exist,
yet the news still came out every day.

01:03:51.086 --> 01:03:54.086
I asked him what I should do.

01:03:54.294 --> 01:03:57.294
He was about 30 years old
and had much more experience.

01:03:57.426 --> 01:04:00.866
I asked him to tell me
where I was making mistakes.

01:04:01.035 --> 01:04:04.555
He told me: "Listen, I can't help you.
I don't think anyone can help you,

01:04:04.764 --> 01:04:11.804
because this has never happened
to anyone in Sweden before."

01:04:12.540 --> 01:04:19.402
I thought about it for a moment
and said: "Only I can help myself".

01:04:20.355 --> 01:04:28.341
To find the streets I should move through.
That's how I'll control the situation.

01:04:28.603 --> 01:04:32.575
I'll allow myself to feel good.
And to play football.

01:04:32.837 --> 01:04:36.802
But If I make mistakes,
I know what I need to do.

01:04:37.017 --> 01:04:41.145
That's why I did everything
on my own. I had no choice...

01:04:41.291 --> 01:04:44.851
My father, Šefik, didn't know
how to advise me.

01:04:45.083 --> 01:04:49.685
He sang, stayed at home,
and had his own war in his head.

01:04:49.885 --> 01:04:54.805
My mother worked as a cleaner,
took care of three children,

01:04:55.029 --> 01:04:57.967
and thought about how she
would feed them.

01:04:58.104 --> 01:05:00.184
She didn't know what
was happening to me.

01:05:00.304 --> 01:05:03.614
The first time I signed a contract
to go to Ajax,

01:05:03.907 --> 01:05:08.820
my mother saw my picture on TV
and thought I had died,

01:05:09.417 --> 01:05:11.857
because usually when someone dies,
they show a photo,

01:05:12.064 --> 01:05:14.691
and her Swedish was poor.

01:05:14.860 --> 01:05:19.300
She saw my photo on TV,
the breaking news,

01:05:19.500 --> 01:05:22.580
and ten seconds later, she called me
to check what had happened.

01:05:22.694 --> 01:05:24.936
I told her then that I was going
to play football for Ajax.

01:05:25.048 --> 01:05:27.546
She insisted that I tell her what
had happened and I explained that

01:05:27.736 --> 01:05:29.882
from now on I would be playing
football professionally.

01:05:30.080 --> 01:05:32.679
She thought I was joking
and hung up the phone.

01:05:32.842 --> 01:05:35.975
She didn't believe I was going
to play football either.

01:05:36.287 --> 01:05:39.413
I didn't have a mentor.

01:05:41.011 --> 01:05:45.011
Someone to guide you,
a teacher to show you what to do.

01:05:45.243 --> 01:05:48.827
Or teammates who believed in me.
No one believed in me.

01:05:49.247 --> 01:05:54.054
You were looking for a new path?
-I looked for it myself and found it.

01:05:54.420 --> 01:05:58.075
I fought, and in the end, I got here.

01:05:58.411 --> 01:06:03.101
That's why I say, if I could do it,
then anyone can do it.

01:06:03.560 --> 01:06:06.031
I am living proof that it works.

